---
#### Document Details
* Title: Java API
* Page: [https://www.onnxruntime.ai/docs/reference/api/java-api.html](https://www.onnxruntime.ai/docs/reference/api/java-api.html)
* Page Source: java-api.md

**Describe the bug**
If DNNL EP is used, a significant memory leak is observed after each call of `Ort::Session.Run(...)` that is made in a new thread. Eventually, it consumes all available memory.

**Urgency**
There are no hard deadlines for this issue.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows 10 20H2 19042.1052
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): Built from source
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.8.0 release (d4106de revision)
- Python version: 3.9.5
- Visual Studio version: Microsoft Visual Studio Community 2019 16.9.4
- GCC/Compiler version: Microsoft C/C++ Optimizing Compiler 19.28.29914 for x64
- CUDA/cuDNN version: Not relevant (issue is observed for CPU execution)
- GPU model and memory: Not relevant (issue is observed for CPU execution)
- Build script: `build.bat --config Release --use_openmp --parallel --cmake_generator "Visual Studio 16 2019" --use_dnnl`

**To Reproduce**
Consider the following code snippet:
```
#include <onnxruntime/core/session/onnxruntime_cxx_api.h>
#include <onnxruntime/core/providers/dnnl/dnnl_provider_factory.h>

#include <thread>

int main()
{
	Ort::Env env{ ORT_LOGGING_LEVEL_WARNING, "env" };

	Ort::SessionOptions sessionOptions;
	OrtSessionOptionsAppendExecutionProvider_Dnnl(sessionOptions, true); // Line 1
	Ort::Session session{ env, L"model.onnx", sessionOptions };

	int64_t inputDims[] = { 8, 640, 1 };
	size_t inputSize = 8 * 640;

	std::vector<float> input(inputSize);
	Ort::Value inputTensor = Ort::Value::CreateTensor<float>(
		Ort::MemoryInfo::CreateCpu(OrtArenaAllocator, OrtMemTypeDefault), input.data(), inputSize, inputDims, 3);

	const char* inputName = "input_1";
	const char* outputName = "output";

	while (true)
	{
		std::thread t([&]() {
			session.Run(Ort::RunOptions{ nullptr }, &inputName, &inputTensor, 1, &outputName, 1);
			});
		t.join();
	}
}
```
If you build and run this code in the Microsoft Visual Studio Community 2019 16.9.4, then you'll see that consumed memory will quickly grow until all available memory is allocated.
Note that:
1) If you comment out Line 1, no memory leak is observed
2) If you call `Ort::Session.Run(...)` in the main thread, no memory leak is observed:
```
while (true)
{
	session.Run(Ort::RunOptions{ nullptr }, &inputName, &inputTensor, 1, &outputName, 1);
}
```
You can find `model.onnx` [here](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1mAHg6Q_C9YKdvPHa8F0z0tdHfJ8-CC9W/view?usp=sharing).

**Expected behaviour**
The expected behaviour is not to have memory leaks (at least significant ones).

**Description**: Implement BatchNormInternal for cuda
- type binding: input/output, scale/bias, mean/var are of separate types, support fp16 case;
- add corresponding forward test cases;
- reenable gradient test case.

**Motivation and Context**
- Original version of BatchNormalization does not support training in fp16, and has issue when updating running_mean/_var.
